@node "INSTALL" "SN LoginConfig v3.2 - Installation Procedures"
@toc "MAIN"
┌───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  SN LoginConfig v3.2 - Installation Procedures
└───────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Installation of SN PFiles is very simple!  Follow these easy steps and
enjoy the true power of CNet and ARexx today.

All SN PFiles are designed to use a common device ("SN:") assigned
to a directory or drive.  It is best when first setting up your SN:
assignment to assign it to a clean (unused) directory or drive.  (i.e.
create a directory in PFiles: called SN and assign SN: PFiles:SN.)
Also, be sure to add this assignment to your Startup-Sequence or
User-Startup so it's there when you reboot!  :)

All you need to do after that is run the installation script for the 
module you wish to install.  More information is given for the current
module while the installation script is running.

───SN/AHI (910) 326-3804 (28.8k)─────────────────────────────────────────
@endnode
@node "SETUP" "SN LoginConfig v3.2 - Setting Things Up
@toc "MAIN"
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
  SN LoginConfig v3.2 - Setting Things Up
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
   
 1  First of all, you should have already executed "LogFig.executeme".
    It will make the directory and copy all files needed into it.  It also
    copies your current sys.welcome to sys.welcome.bak AND to
    SN:LogFig/_Config.All-YOURS, renames the included _Config.All to
    _Config.All-MINE (this is mine I've included for an example) and
    finally replaces your sys.welcome with NEW.sys.welcome.  This new
    sys.welcome runs the program, LoginConfigRun.

 2  Edit the _Config.#? files to the way you want your users to be able
    to configure their logins.

    a.  The FIRST MANDATORY files executed should be placed in _Config.Begin.

    b.  The MIDDLE OPTIONAL files executed should be placed in _Config.Added.
        Note the format of the example file!  First line is the actual
        execution command and the second is the description of it the users
        will see.

    c.  The LAST MANDATORY files executed should be placed in _Config.End.

    d.  The special login sequences, _Config.HiSpeed, _Config.LDSpeed and
        _Config.NewUser, should be modified to suit, also.  They are what
        the respective users see if opted for (in the case of the first
        two.)  New users always use the _Config.NewUser sequence.

    (Included are my files for you to follow.  They're just like your
    normal sys.welcome files, so it's no biggie.)

 3  _Config.All-YOURS should now be your old sys.welcome file.
    It's safe to just rename _Config.All-YOURS to _Config.All,
    but I've left that up to you, because you're probably going
    to be making alot of changes.  (Moving this line to this file,
    etc.)  A good way to reconstruct your _Config.All is to, first,
    edit _Config.Begin, Added and End.  Once done, your _Config.All
    should be your _Config.Begin on top, your _Config.Added (without
    descriptions, of course) in the middle and your _Config.End on
    the bottom.  AND!!!  You need to add one more line to your
    _Config.All once it's ready.  That line is included in the file
    _Add2EndOfConfig.All.

 4  Modify SysOp configurable variables in SN:LogFig/LoginConfigRun.

    a.  pfp="SN:LogFig/_Config."  /* Path/File Prefix */
        localc="910 919"          /* (*=ALL) Local Area Codes */
        hiaccs="10 30 31"         /* (*=ALL) Levels Allowed to Use HiSpeed */
        mraccs="*"                /* (*=ALL) Levels Allowed to Use OMR-Grabber/Upload */
        mcaccs="*"                /* (*=ALL) Levels Allowed to Use MailCheck */
        skiprs="1 72"             /* (*=ALL) UserIDs Allowed to Skip Login */
        showfirst=0               /* Show _Config.All before users configure? (0=NO) */
        logging=2                 /* 0=None, 1=CNet, 2=SN Userlogs, 3=Both */

    b.  If you're using the standard "SN:Logfig/" setup, the first line
        is fine.  The local area codes line is used to determine who should
        be allowed to use the LDSpeed login.  Use as many as needed in your
        area, seperated by a space.  (Follow the example.)  The next three
        govern what levels get to see the special pre-logins.  The skip
        login uses ID#'s instead of levels, allowing only one or a certain
        few to skip the entire login sequence.  Note that using "*" will
        allow ALL access levels to use it.

    c.  ShowFirst determines whether you want users who have NOT selected
        a config yet to see everything in the _Config.All BEFORE they get
        to choose.  If yes, they'll go through everything, then be asked
        to customize.  Otherwise, they'll be asked to customize first and
        go from there.

    d.  Logging:  4 options here.  First is no logging.  You'll never know
        what choice users made unless you're watching.  Second adds a
        line telling you what they did in CNet's calls log.  Third adds
        the line to SN's UserLogs.  The last option does both.

 5  Modify SysOp configurable variables in SN:LogFig/LoginConfig.

    a.  pth="SN:LogFig/"      /* Location of _Config files */
        askem=0               /* Ask/Force customize 0=FORCE 1=ASK */

    b.  Path variable above (pth) should be the same as the pfp variable
        in LoginConfigRun.

    c.  When LoginConfig is executed, either automatically from the
        end of your default _Config.All or manually by the LOGIN command,
        this determines whether the user is asked or forced to customize
        their login sequence.  If it's not forced and they say no, they
        will continue using the default login sequence (_Config.All)
        until they opt to do so.

 6  Make the required BBSTEXT/BBSMENU modifications:

    ** See the now seperate file, LF32_Cut-n-Paste, for details on all
       BBSTEXT/BBSMENU modifications.

 7  Verify that your new sys.welcome says:
       {#0SN:LogFig/LoginConfigRun}

    If it doesn't for some reason, make it so.

 8  Add "LOGIN |{#0SN:LogFig/LoginConfig}" to your menu (and add the
    option to your main menu) so users can modify their configurations at
    will after their first login with the default sequence.  Note that the
    above { is actually a control-Q command.

 9  Add "LCRESET |{#1SN:LogFig/LoginConfig RESET}" to your BBSMENU under
    1; Maintenance menu.  When ran, it will reset all your users configs,
    in case you change any of your config files and want them to use
    them (duh).  This is a good idea.  Anytime you change the _Config.
    All, Added, Begin or End files, RESET!

